  <h1>Types of Retaliation Claims</h1>
  <p><em>Reviewed by Riley Chen (RC), Employment &amp; Civil Rights Practice Lead. Updated May 2026.</em></p>
  <h2>Title VII / civil rights retaliation</h2><p>Filing an EEOC charge, making an internal harassment or discrimination complaint, or participating in an investigation. The most common retaliation claim. Burlington Northern standard: any materially adverse action that would dissuade a reasonable employee.</p>
  <h2>FLSA wage retaliation</h2><p>Filing a complaint about unpaid wages, overtime violations, or minimum wage. No EEOC exhaustion required. Liquidated damages double back pay. 2-year statute of limitations (3 for willful).</p>
  <h2>OSHA / safety retaliation</h2><p>Reporting safety violations to OSHA or refusing to perform imminently dangerous work. Must file with OSHA within 30 days — the shortest deadline in employment law. OSHA Section 11(c).</p>
  <h2>Workers&rsquo; compensation retaliation</h2><p>State law claim. Filing a workers&rsquo; comp claim or threatening to do so is protected. Remedies vary by state but often include reinstatement, back pay, and in some states (California) additional penalties. Statute of limitations: typically 1–3 years.</p>
  <h2>Whistleblower protection</h2><p>Dodd-Frank (SEC/CFTC fraud), Sarbanes-Oxley (corporate securities fraud), False Claims Act (government contractor fraud), and state whistleblower laws. FCA qui tam relators can receive 15–30% of government recovery in addition to anti-retaliation remedies.</p>
